Why Jerome Powell has to go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – thus to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have far-reaching consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to regulate the banking system adequately, and thus paved the way for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' reaction to it had far-reaching political consequences; it exacerbated inequality and nourished a lasting feeling of discontent among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a multitude of clichés as to why the current central bank chief Jerome Powell should be confirmed in his position.
It would be a proof of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
We need someone with experience who would lead us through the recovery in the wake of the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I've heard 25 years ago, when I was the head of the economic advisory board of US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker a second term, after he had tamed the inflation.
Reagan owed a lot to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an adherent of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to goal conflicts are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets will be efficient, stable, fair, and driven by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always held clearly different, but clearly articulated views on these questions (at least until the Republicans fell prey to populist madness).
From my perspective, the Democrats are right to worry about the consequences of unemployment.
The crisis of 2008 has shown that unbridled markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, it is only in times of tense labor markets that marginalized groups are drawn into the economy and wage differences are reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for every US central bank chief.
Already now, the US is faced with difficult decisions about what to do against inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially minor issues that arise from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, which still hasn't recovered to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and thereby an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the wrong pricing of mortgage-backed securities was a key factor in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even more severe and widespread mispricing of assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do about this?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
Firstly, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thus risked the financial health of our world.
And even now he hesitates to do something regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers worldwide have meanwhile declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues do not belong to the mandate of the Fed, but he would be wrong.
This belongs to the task of the Fed to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record on this suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
A laxity of this kind is exactly what the economy can't afford right now.
A blatant lack of competition and inadequate regulation already enable excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give the dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators attribute praise to Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But every second-year student would have known that you shouldn't tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argued, Powell doesn't feel particularly committed to full employment.
Instead: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve was marked in the past decade by a series of flawed decisions on monetary policy, which date back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not a matter for the central bank, it is a fact that the bank's policy has important distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as premature interest rate hikes can strangle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal over stock trades by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump, the trust in US institutions has already been weakened, and there is now a real risk that the trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock transactions would appear unseemly.
The Fed is similar to the US Supreme Court in certain respects.
This is supposed to be above politics, but as we know since Bush v. Gore, this is not the case.
Trump has made it clear for everyone who had any doubts.
Also, the Fed is supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan, by following the deregulation agenda of their party, have clearly shown that this is not the case either.
However, while the central bank council makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power traditionally concentrates in the hands of the central bank chief – much stronger than with the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank chief who decides what comes to the vote and which topics are put on the backburner or forced forward.
The climate issue is just one example where it is extremely important who sits at the head of the table.
The US needs a central bank that truly commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competition-determined financial sector.
Whoever believes we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation is already too far-reaching lacks vision.
We don't need an ideologue like Greenspan or a lawyer aligned with Wall Street like Powell.
We need someone with a deep understanding of economics and who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated their abilities.
Lael Brainard sits already on the central bank council, where she has shown her competence and won the trust of the markets – without making any compromises on her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chief who maintains continuity and does not disturb the markets, but who shares his economic and social program.
